Poisoning, pork - China (Guangdong): RFI 20011116.2820
Date: 9 Nov 2001
From: K.Yip Associates kyipassociates@yahoo.com>
Source: Xinhuanet news [edited
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2001-11/09/content_107376.htm>

Medicine-taking Pigs Blamed for Poisoning
-----------------------------------------
More than 500 victims of food poisoning in Heyuan of Southern Guangdong
Province are suspected to have eaten meat of pigs fed with a particular
medicine to curb asthma. [In all likelihood this was clenbuterol. -
Mod.TG The poisonous pork were all purchased from local bazaars on
Wednesday.
To help establish the cause of the poisoning, Heyuan government has
banned sales of pork in the whole city for 3 days, to end Friday, for
further investigation. All the pork suspected of being poisonous has been
secured.
The investigation's findings will be made public in 3 days, an official
with the local government Huang Juping was quoted as saying.
The victims have reported in stable condition or recovering in local
hospitals. The symptoms encompassed vomiting, headache, and a rapid
heart beat, following breakfast and lunch on Wednesday morning. They
gradually made their way to see doctors from around half past 9 that
morning.
Doctors said the illness is only life-threatening if medical treatment
is not received in time.
To date, it is the biggest pork poisoning case to have taken place in
the province, which borders Hong Kong and Macao. Heyuan is about 200
kilometers northeast of Guangzhou, the provincial
capital.
So far, no suspects have been detained.
